\\n**2. Testbench Improvement (Queue Implementation):**\\n    *   **Sequential Logic:** Since `TopModule` is an FSM, the queue-based approach is mandatory. \\n    *   **MAX_QUEUE_SIZE:** The specification suggests a size based on pattern detection (up to 8 bits for the flag pattern). Following the constraints (Max 10), I set `MAX_QUEUE_SIZE = 10`.\\n    *   **Queue Contents:** The queues will store the necessary comparison points: Input (`clk`, `reset`, `in`), Got Output (`disc_dut`, `flag_dut`, `err_dut`), Expected Output (`disc_ref`, `flag_ref`, `err_ref`), and Reset state.\\n    *   **Synchronization:** All queue operations (push, pop, checking) must occur inside `always @(posedge clk, negedge clk)` to match the sequential nature of the FSM and the original timing structure.\\n    *   **Mismatch Detection:** The comparison logic (`disc_ref !== disc_dut`, etc.) will be performed cycle-by-cycle. The first time a mismatch occurs, the queue will be dumped with detailed cycle information, as required.\\n    *   **Final Reporting:** The original `stats1` structure\'s purpose (total count and first time) will be replicated by tracking these values during the queue process. Upon simulation end, the final pass/fail message must be printed exactly as specified: \\"SIMULATION PASSED\\" or \\"SIMULATION FAILED - x MISMATCHES DETECTED, FIRST AT TIME y\\".\\n\\n**3. Golden Testbench Adherence & Modification:**\\n    *   The stimulus generator (`stimulus_gen`), the reference module (`RefModule`), and the instantiation of `TopModule` are kept identical.\\n    *   The original complex comparison logic (`tb_match`) is replaced by the queue-driven verification.\\n    *   The original `final` block is replaced with logic that uses the collected mismatch data from the queue process to produce the required final output.\\n\\n**4. Advice to Avoid Syntax Errors:**\\n    *   Maintain strict type consistency within the queue elements (using `logic` or `reg` appropriately for 1-bit signals).\\n    *   Ensure the `always` block for queue management uses the correct sensitivity list (`posedge clk, negedge clk`).\\n    *   Carefully handle the indexing and deletion/pushing operations in the queue logic to prevent array overflow or underflow.\\n\\nThis approach maintains the functionality while satisfying the complex, specific reporting requirements for sequential logic testing.",\n    "interface": "module TopModule (\\n    input clk,\\n    input reset,\\n    input in,\\n    output disc,\\n    output flag,\\n    output err\\n);\\n    // Module body is assumed to be implemented elsewhere\\nendmodule",\n    "testbench": "`timescale 1 ps/1 ps\\n`define OK 12\\n`define INCORRECT 13\\n\\n\\nmodule stimulus_gen (\\n\\tinput clk,\\n\\toutput logic reset, in\\n);\\n\\n\\t\\tinitial begin\\n\\t\\t\\treset <= 1;\\n\\t\\t\\tin <= 0;\\n\\t\\t\\t@(posedge clk);\\n\\t\\t\\trepeat(800) @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\\n\\t\\t\\t\\treset <= !($random & 31);\\n\\t\\t\\t\\tin <= |($random&7);\\n\\t\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\t\\t#1 $finish;\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\t\\tendmodule\\n\\nmodule tb();\\n\\n\\t\\t// Data structure to hold error statistics (adapted from golden testbench)\\n\\t\\ttypedef struct packed {\\n\\t\\t\\tint errors;\\n\\t\\t\\tint errortime;\\n\\t\\t\\tint errors_disc;\\n\\t\\t\\tint errortime_disc;\\n\\t\\t\\tint errors_flag;\\n\\t\\t\\tint errortime_flag;\\n\\t\\t\\tint errors_err;\\n\\t\\t\\tint errortime_err;\\n\\t\\t\\tint clocks;\\n\\t} stats;\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\tstats stats1;\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\twire[511:0] wavedrom_title;\\n\\t\\twire wavedrom_enable;\\n\\t\\tint wavedrom_hide_after_time;\\n\\t\\t\\n\\t\\treg clk=0;\\n\\t\\tinitial forever\\n\\t\\t\\t#5 clk = ~clk;\\n\\t\\tend\\n\\n\\t\\tlogic reset;\\n\\t\\tlogic in;\\n\\t\\tlogic disc_ref;\\n\\t\\tlogic disc_dut;\\n\\t\\tlogic flag_ref;\\n\\t\\tlogic flag_dut;\\n\\t\\tlogic err_ref;\\n\\t\\tlogic err_dut;\\n\\n\\t\\t// --- Queue Definitions for Mismatch Detection ---\\n\\t\\tlocalparam MAX_QUEUE_SIZE = 10;\\n\\t\\t\\